The photon energy fromthe helium lamp is  

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
      =\frac{(6.626\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s})(3.00\times10^{8}\,\text{m/s})}
             {58.4\times10^{-9}\,\text{m}}
      =3.40\times10^{-18}\ \text{J}
\]

The kinetic energy of the emitted electrons is  

\[
K=\frac12 mv^{2}
   =\frac12 (9.109\times10^{-31}\,\text{kg})(1.59\times10^{6}\,\text{m/s})^{2}
   =1.15\times10^{-18}\ \text{J}
\]

From the photoelectric equation  

\[
E_{\text{photon}} = \phi + K \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\phi = E_{\text{photon}}-K = 3.40\times10^{-18}\ \text{J} - 1.15\times10^{-18}\ \text{J}
      =2.25\times10^{-18}\ \text{J}
\]

Convert the work function (ionization energy) to electron‑volts:

\[
\phi_{\text{eV}} = \frac{2.25\times10^{-18}\ \text{J}}{1.602\times10^{-19}\ \text{J/eV}}
                 \approx 14.1\ \text{eV}
\]

\[
\boxed{\text{Ionization energy of krypton } \approx 14.1\ \text{eV}}
\]

#### 14.1

The kinetic energy of the block is transformed into elastic potential energy of the spring at the point of maximum compression.

\[
\frac12 m v^{2}= \frac12 k x^{2}
\]

Solve for the compression \(x\):

\[
x = v\sqrt{\frac{m}{k}}
\]

Insert the given values  

\[
m = 2\ \text{kg},\qquad v = 4\ \text{m/s},\qquad k = 6\ \text{N/m}
\]

\[
x = 4\ \text{m/s}\;\sqrt{\frac{2\ \text{kg}}{6\ \text{N/m}}}
   = 4\ \sqrt{\frac{1}{3}}
   = 4 \times \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
   \approx 4 \times 0.57735
   \approx 2.31\ \text{m}
\]

Thus the spring is compressed by about **2.3 m** at its maximum.

