#### 0.139

The horse’s work can be found from the heat supplied to the water.

**1. Energy needed to heat thewater**

\[
\begin{aligned}
m_{\text{water}} &= 11.6\ \text{kg}=1.16\times10^{4}\ \text{g}\\[2pt]
c_{\text{water}} &= 4.18\ \frac{\text{J}}{\text{g·K}}\\[2pt]
\Delta T &= 355\ \text{K}-273\ \text{K}=82\ \text{K}\\[2pt]
Q &= m\,c\,\Delta T = (1.16\times10^{4}\,\text{g})(4.18\,\frac{\text{J}}{\text{g·K}})(82\ \text{K})\\
  &= 3.98\times10^{6}\ \text{J}
\end{aligned}
\]

**2. Power delivered by the horse**

Time for heating: \(2.5\ \text{h}=2.5\times3600\ \text{s}=9.0\times10^{3}\ \text{s}\).

\[
P = \frac{Q}{t}= \frac{3.98\times10^{6}\ \text{J}}{9.0\times10^{3}\ \text{s}}
   \approx 4.42\times10^{2}\ \text{W}
\]

**3. Work the horse could do in 2.5 min**

\[
t_{\text{lift}} = 2.5\ \text{min}=150\ \text{s}
\]
\[
W = P\,t_{\text{lift}} = (4.42\times10^{2}\ \text{W})(150\ \text{s})
   \approx 6.63\times10^{4}\ \text{J}
\]

**4. Height the 225 kg weight could be raised**

\[
W = m g h \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
h = \frac{W}{m g}
   = \frac{6.63\times10^{4}\ \text{J}}{(225\ \text{kg})(9.81\ \text{m/s}^2)}
   \approx 3.0\times10^{1}\ \text{m}
\]

\[
\boxed{h \approx 30\ \text{m}}
\]

#### 30

**Step 1 – Resolve the initial velocity into components**

\[
v_{0}=200\ \text{m/s},\qquad \theta =60^{\circ}
\]

\[
v_{x}=v_{0}\cos\theta =200\cos 60^{\circ}=200(0.5)=100\ \text{m/s}
\]

\[
v_{y0}=v_{0}\sin\theta =200\sin 60^{\circ}=200\left(\frac{\sqrt3}{2}\right)=100\sqrt3\ \text{m/s}
\]

**Step 2 – Time of flight**

The projectile returns to the launch height when its vertical displacement is zero:

\[
y(t)=v_{y0}t-\frac12gt^{2}=0\quad\Longrightarrow\quad t\bigl(v_{y0}-\tfrac12gt\bigr)=0
\]

The non‑zero root gives the total flight time

\[
t_{\text{flight}}=\frac{2v_{y0}}{g}
      =\frac{2(100\sqrt3)}{9.81}\approx 35.1\ \text{s}
\]

**Step 3 – Vertical velocity at impact**

\[
v_{y}=v_{y0}-gt_{\text{flight}}
     =100\sqrt3-9.81\left(\frac{2(100\sqrt3)}{9.81}\right)
     =-100\sqrt3\ \text{m/s}
\]

Thus the vertical component has the same magnitude as at launch but opposite sign.

**Step 4 – Speed at impact**

The horizontal component does not change (no air resistance):

\[
v_{x}=100\ \text{m/s}
\]

The speed (magnitude of the velocity) at impact is

\[
v =\sqrt{v_{x}^{2}+v_{y}^{2}}
   =\sqrt{(100)^{2}+(-100\sqrt3)^{2}}
   =\sqrt{100^{2}+100^{2}\cdot3}
   =\sqrt{4\cdot100^{2}}
   =200\ \text{m/s}
\]

So the projectile hits the ground with the same speed it left the ground.

#### 200

The energy of a photon of wavelength λ is  

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
\]

where  

* \(h = 6.626\times10^{-34}\ \text{J·s}\) (Planck constant)  
* \(c = 3.00\times10^{8}\ \text{m·s}^{-1}\) (speed of light)  
* \(\lambda = 300\ \text{nm}=3.00\times10^{-7}\ \text{m}\)

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{6.626\times10^{-34}\times3.00\times10^{8}}{3.00\times10^{-7}}
= \frac{1.9878\times10^{-25}}{3.00\times10^{-7}}
= 6.626\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}
\]

Energy per mole is obtained by multiplying by Avogadro’s number \(N_{\!A}=6.022\times10^{23}\ \text{mol}^{-1}\):

\[
E_{\text{mol}} = E_{\text{photon}}\,N_{\!A}
= 6.626\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}\times6.022\times10^{23}
= 3.99\times10^{5}\ \text{J·mol}^{-1}
\]

Convert to kilojoules per mole:

\[
E_{\text{mol}} = \frac{3.99\times10^{5}\ \text{J}}{10^{3}} \approx 3.99\times10^{2}\ \text{kJ·mol}^{-1}
= 399\ \text{kJ·mol}^{-1}
\]

A typical single‑bond energy is about \(400\ \text{kJ·mol}^{-1}\).  
Thus the UV photon of 300 nm carries essentially the same amount of energy as breaking a single covalent bond.

#### 399

The vibrational frequency of a diatomic molecule in the harmonic‑oscillator approximation is  

\[
\nu = \frac{1}{2\pi}\sqrt{\frac{k}{\mu}}
\]

where  

* \(k\) = force constant (N m\(^{-1}\))  
* \(\mu\) = reduced mass of the two atoms (kg)  

The wavenumber \(\tilde{\nu}\) (in cm\(^{-1}\)) is obtained from  

\[
\tilde{\nu}= \frac{\nu}{c}
\]

with \(c = 2.9979\times10^{10}\,\text{cm s}^{-1}\).

---

### 1. Reduced mass of \({}^{35}\text{Cl}_2\)

Atomic mass of \({}^{35}\text{Cl}\) ≈ 34.96885 u  

\(1\;\text{u}=1.660539\times10^{-27}\,\text{kg}\)

\[
m_{\text{Cl}} = 34.96885\;\text{u}\times 1.660539\times10^{-27}\,\frac{\text{kg}}{\text{u}}
           \approx 5.807\times10^{-26}\,\text{kg}
\]

For two identical atoms  

\[
\mu = \frac{m_{\text{Cl}}}{2}
    \approx \frac{5.807\times10^{-26}}{2}
    = 2.903\times10^{-26}\,\text{kg}
\]

---

### 2. Harmonic‑oscillator frequency (Hz)

\[
\frac{k}{\mu}= \frac{319\;\text{N m}^{-1}}{2.903\times10^{-26}\,\text{kg}}
            \approx 1.10\times10^{28}\,\text{s}^{-2}
\]

\[
\sqrt{\frac{k}{\mu}} \approx \sqrt{1.10\times10^{28}}
                     = 1.05\times10^{14}\,\text{s}^{-1}
\]

\[
\nu = \frac{1}{2\pi}\sqrt{\frac{k}{\mu}}
    = \frac{1.05\times10^{14}}{2\pi}
    \approx 1.67\times10^{13}\,\text{Hz}
\]

---

### 3. Convert to wavenumber (cm\(^{-1}\))

\[
\tilde{\nu}= \frac{\nu}{c}
           = \frac{1.67\times10^{13}\,\text{s}^{-1}}
                  {2.998\times10^{10}\,\text{cm s}^{-1}}
           \approx 5.56\times10^{2}\,\text{cm}^{-1}
\]

---

\[
\boxed{\tilde{\nu}\;\approx\;5.6\times10^{2}\ \text{cm}^{-1}}
\]

Thus the fundamental vibrational frequency of \({}^{35}\text{Cl}^{35}\text{Cl}\) is about **\(5.6\times10^{2}\,\text{cm}^{-1}\)**.  

